 # Critical Workflow After Grok Makes Changes #

  ALWAYS follow this sequence:

  1. User says: "Grok made changes, check and commit" (or similar)
  2. Claude Code MUST run:
  git status
  3. Claude Code MUST run:
  git diff
  3. (or git diff <file> for each modified file)
  4. Claude Code shows user: What files changed and brief summary
  5. User confirms: Looks good
  6. Claude Code commits: All related files together with proper message
  7. Claude Code pushes: If requested

  NEVER:
  - ❌ Commit without running git status first
  - ❌ Commit only some modified files (check ALL)
  - ❌ Assume you know what changed without verifying

  # Complete Session Close Workflow #

  The 3-Step Process

  Step 1: Commit Code Changes

  Save your actual work (the code you wrote/modified) to Git.

  git add [files you changed]
  git commit -m "description of what you did"

  Why first? Code is the substance. If your session crashes, at least your work is saved.

  ---
  Step 2: Update Memory Bank

  Tell Claude: "I have concluded this coding session. Please review our entire chat history since the last memory bank update
  and perform the memory bank update. This is a multi-step task, so use the Agent."

  Claude will update:
  - memory-bank-activeContext.md (concise summary)
  - session_history.md (detailed technical notes)

  Why? Documents what you did so the next Claude session knows where you left off.

  ---
  Step 3: Commit Memory Bank + Push Everything

  Save the documentation and backup everything to GitHub.

  git add memory-bank/
  git commit -m "docs: update Memory Bank to v2.XX"
  git push

  Why? Backs up all your work (code + documentation) to the cloud.

  ---
  Quick Check

  After Step 3, run git status - you should see:
  On branch main
  Your branch is up to date with 'origin/main'.
  nothing to commit, working tree clean

  This means everything is saved and pushed. ✅

  ---
  Key Terms

  - Commit = Save changes to Git on your computer (local)
  - Push = Upload commits from your computer to GitHub (cloud backup)
  - Memory Bank = Documentation files that help Claude remember your project

  ---
  Why This Order?

  1. Code first - Most important, save it ASAP
  2. Memory Bank second - Documents the code changes
  3. Push last - Backs up everything to GitHub

  If anything crashes mid-process, you've already saved the critical parts.


> # I thought "Git" was short for "GitHub", not so? #

⏺ No - they're different things:

  Git

  - Software installed on your computer
  - Tracks changes to your files (version control)
  - Works locally (offline, on your machine)
  - Created in 2005 by Linus Torvalds

  GitHub

  - Website/cloud service (github.com)
  - Stores Git repositories online
  - Allows backup and sharing
  - Owned by Microsoft

  ---
  The Relationship

  Git = The tool that saves your work locallyGitHub = The online place where you back it up

  Analogy:
  - Git = Taking photos with your camera
  - GitHub = Uploading photos to iCloud/Google Photos

  ---
  Why Both?

  1. Git (local) = Fast, works offline, you control it
  2. GitHub (cloud) = Backup, accessible anywhere, shareable

  You can use Git without GitHub (just local saving), but GitHub needs Git to work.

  ---
  In Your Workflow

  - git commit = Save with Git (local)
  - git push = Upload to GitHub (cloud)


