  # Quick Reference: Using Grok as Backup for Claude Code #

  When to Use Grok

  - Claude Code is throttled (rate limited)
  - Simple tasks only: bug fixes, UI tweaks, small features
  - NOT for: complex refactoring, architecture, Memory Bank updates

  How to Switch to Grok in Cline

  1. Open Cline panel in VS Code
  2. Click "Model" dropdown (top of panel)
  3. Select: x-ai/grok-code-fast-1 (FREE)

  Working with Grok

  1. Describe task in Cline chat
  2. Let Grok make changes
  3. Ask Grok: "Run tsc and eslint to check for errors"
  4. If clean: Commit with git add . && git commit -m "description"
  5. If errors: Ask Grok to fix them

  Testing Commands (Grok can run these)

  - TypeScript: npx tsc --noEmit
  - ESLint: npx eslint .
  - Or just ask: "Check for TypeScript and ESLint errors"

  Return to Claude Code

  - When throttling ends, start fresh session
  - Tell Claude: "Update Memory Bank"
  - Claude reads git history and updates Memory Bank with ALL changes

  Remember

  - ✅ Grok is FREE but less reliable
  - ✅ Always test Grok's work
  - ✅ Use for simple tasks only
  - ✅ Git commits preserve everything
  - ❌ Don't use Grok for complex features
